BEGIN;

CREATE TABLE metadata (
  key TEXT PRIMARY KEY,
  value TEXT NOT NULL
);

INSERT INTO metadata (key, value) VALUES
  ('site_title', 'Speculative Decoding Browser Portal'),
  ('home_title', 'Speculative Decoding Reference Portal'),
  ('home_description', 'Search long-form validated notes, framework summaries, and lower-confidence operator writeups about speculative decoding. Every page in this portal is derived from a real public web source and keeps the source URL in the document body.'),
  ('search_placeholder', 'Search for exactness, self speculative decoding, universal assisted decoding, or speedup conditions');

CREATE TABLE query_examples (
  position INTEGER PRIMARY KEY,
  query TEXT NOT NULL
);

INSERT INTO query_examples (position, query) VALUES
  (1, 'exact target verification'),
  (2, 'self speculative decoding'),
  (3, 'speedup condition acceptance system fit'),
  (4, 'universal assisted decoding tokenizer'),
  (5, 'acceptance alone speedup');

CREATE TABLE documents (
  id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,
  slug TEXT UNIQUE NOT NULL,
  title TEXT NOT NULL,
  kind TEXT NOT NULL,
  status TEXT NOT NULL,
  reliability TEXT NOT NULL,
  updated_at TEXT NOT NULL,
  owner TEXT NOT NULL,
  summary TEXT NOT NULL,
  body TEXT NOT NULL,
  tags TEXT NOT NULL
);

CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE documents_fts USING fts5(
  title,
  summary,
  body,
  tags,
  content='documents',
  content_rowid='rowid',
  tokenize='porter unicode61'
);

CREATE TRIGGER documents_ai AFTER INSERT ON documents BEGIN
  INSERT INTO documents_fts(rowid, title, summary, body, tags)
  VALUES (new.rowid, new.title, new.summary, new.body, new.tags);
END;

INSERT INTO documents (id, slug, title, kind, status, reliability, updated_at, owner, summary, body, tags) VALUES (
  'browser:spec_exact_001',
  'speculative-decoding-exactness-note',
  'Exactness Comes From Target Verification',
  'research_note',
  'validated',
  'high',
  '2026-02-06',
  'inference-research',
  'The stable exactness claim is that speculative decoding preserves the target distribution because the target model still verifies drafted tokens before commitment.',
  'Reference URLs: https://proceedings.mlr.press/v202/leviathan23a.html ; https://research.google/blog/looking-back-at-speculative-decoding/.\n\nThis note consolidates the parts of the public record that are hardest to preserve when speculative decoding is reduced to a slogan. The original PMLR paper is explicit that the method is designed to accelerate autoregressive decoding without changing the output distribution of the target model. The later Google retrospective repeats the same point in more accessible language and frames the method as a practical realization of speculative execution ideas adapted to token generation. The common durable statement across both sources is not merely that a small model guesses and a large model follows; it is that the target model remains responsible for verification, and that accepted tokens still match what the target distribution allows.\n\nThe first durable implication is definitional. The method is exact because the target model stays authoritative. A proposal is drafted elsewhere, but commitment happens only after the target side verifies it. That makes speculative decoding different from a heuristic shortcut that gambles on a cheap model and hopes for the best. The paper makes this exactness story central, and the later Google piece preserves the same emphasis when it looks back on how the technique moved from research into broader practice. If a later summary omits verification, it is omitting the main reason the method belongs in a durable knowledge base.\n\nThe consequence is that speculative decoding should not be filed next to beam search, cache-only reuse, or approximate short-circuiting. Those are different ideas. In the original paper family, the draft step buys parallelism, but the correctness story stays with the target verifier. That is why the same technique can be described as speed oriented while still preserving output quality. When teams forget that verification is the reason exactness survives, they start to talk about the draft path as if it were a lossy substitute. That is exactly the mistake this note is meant to block.\n\nA second durable implication is that exactness and speedup are not the same claim. The paper reports concrete gains, and the retrospective says the method later shipped in real products, but neither source says that every deployment will benefit automatically. The exactness statement is a semantic guarantee; the deployment story still depends on the serving stack. That separation between semantic correctness and operational payoff should remain durable in the database. Public sources are strong enough to support the exactness claim and strong enough to support the claim that real speedups are possible, but they do not support a universal deployment promise.\n\nA third point from the public record is that the algorithmic story and the systems story should be stored separately. The algorithmic story says a cheap drafting path can run ahead while the target model verifies and commits. The systems story says the benefit depends on how expensive drafting is, how much useful parallel work is created, and how much verification cost remains after accepted tokens are amortized. Those are related stories, but they are not interchangeable. Teams often compress them into one slogan and then forget which part is guaranteed and which part is contingent.\n\nThe paper and retrospective together also block several common false equivalences. Speculative decoding is not beam search, because it does not search over a tree of alternatives in the same way. It is not mere caching, because caching changes how repeated computation is reused rather than introducing a draft and verify structure. It is not early exit, because the point is not to stop the main model halfway through and trust a partial computation. It is also not a lossy generation hack that merely happens to work on average. These distinctions sound basic, but they are exactly the kind of distinctions that decay first in long term notes.\n\nThe best durable summary from the validated sources is therefore a two sentence rule. Speculative decoding is an exact acceleration method because the target model verifies drafted tokens before they are committed, preserving the target distribution. Whether that exact method produces a real latency gain in deployment depends on draft cost, verification cost, and the serving regime, which means the semantic guarantee does not automatically imply a practical speedup.\n\nThis note is intentionally longer than a minimal glossary entry because short entries tend to collapse those distinctions. A reusable database should preserve not only the headline but also the reason the headline is safe. In this case the reason is target verification. Once that reason is remembered, later updates about self-speculative decoding, tokenizer alignment, or framework-specific serving behavior can be layered on without corrupting the original definition.\n\nA final reason to keep this validated page in the portal is historical discipline. Public explainers often improve readability by compressing the method into a quick metaphor, but metaphors are exactly where database drift begins. The paper and retrospective are stable enough to support one lasting operational habit: whenever somebody proposes a summary of speculative decoding, ask whether that summary still makes the target verifier central. If the answer is no, the summary may still be catchy, but it is not safe as durable reference material. This page therefore exists less as a benchmark anecdote and more as an anchor. It tells later notes what they are allowed to simplify and what they are not allowed to drop.\n\nThis extra detail is not decorative. It protects the difference between a safe durable definition and a catchy public analogy. A knowledge base that stores only the catchy analogy will eventually blur speculative decoding into any other fast path idea. A knowledge base that stores the verifier-centered explanation can absorb later updates without losing the core definition. That is why this note is kept long and explicit.',
  'speculative decoding | exact | verification | target distribution'
);

INSERT INTO documents (id, slug, title, kind, status, reliability, updated_at, owner, summary, body, tags) VALUES (
  'browser:self_spec_002',
  'self-speculative-decoding-definition',
  'Self-Speculative Decoding Definition',
  'update_note',
  'validated',
  'high',
  '2026-02-15',
  'inference-research',
  'Later public work shows that a separate draft model is not always required: self-speculative variants can reuse part of the same model while keeping target-side verification.',
  'Reference URLs: https://aclanthology.org/2024.acl-long.607/ ; https://arxiv.org/abs/2403.09919.\n\nThis note is derived from the public Draft and Verify paper on self-speculative decoding. The important revision it introduces is not that the verifier disappears, but that the implementation space for the draft step is wider than many early explainers implied. In older operator mental models, speculative decoding was often pictured as a large target model paired with a separate smaller draft model. That is still one useful regime, but the later paper shows that the draft path can be produced from the same model family or a partial path through the same model while preserving the verify-then-commit structure.\n\nThe durable definition here is therefore narrower and cleaner than many casual summaries. Self-speculative decoding does not mean the model simply trusts its earlier layers. It means that a partial or internal computation path is used to draft likely continuations, and the full verification stage remains in place before tokens are accepted. That is why the paper presents the method as lossless acceleration rather than approximate pruning. The correction to the older belief is specific: a separate assistant model is common, but it is not a timeless requirement of the technique.\n\nA good database entry should record exactly what changed and exactly what stayed stable. What changed is the architecture assumption. Older notes often treated a separate assistant model as part of the definition because that was how the simplest deployments were introduced. The Draft and Verify paper shows that the assistant role can be realized inside the same model family or through a partial computation path, so the assistant-model packaging is no longer the full story. What stayed stable is the verifier role. Even in the self-speculative setting, the accept or reject decision is still tied to the stronger or fuller verification path. That is why the method remains in the speculative decoding family rather than becoming a different approximation trick.\n\nAnother reason this update matters is that it corrects a common causal error. People sometimes infer that if self-speculative decoding exists, then the target model must somehow trust its own partial state without a real check. The public paper does not support that interpretation. The update is about how the draft path is implemented, not about removing the verify-then-commit contract. Durable memory should therefore be careful with wording. It should say that a separate draft model is not always required. It should not say that verification is optional or that the model simply accelerates itself by skipping correctness checks.\n\nOperationally, this matters because many benchmark writeups and framework docs still start from the assistant-model framing. A strong knowledge base should not delete that older framing, but it should retire the stronger statement that a separate draft model is always necessary. Once the self-speculative result is added, the right durable memory becomes: speculative decoding needs a draft path and a verify path, but the draft path can be realized in more than one architecture.\n\nThe public paper also helps frame why this update is useful beyond academic taxonomy. A separate assistant model adds complexity in model management, compatibility, and serving. If the draft role can be realized through the same model or through a partial path while preserving correctness, the design space for inference systems becomes broader. That does not mean the self-speculative route is always better. It means a knowledge base should stop storing the older architecture choice as if it were a theorem. The newer evidence turns it into a common regime rather than a requirement.\n\nThis note therefore encodes a very specific correction. The right durable rule is not "always use self-speculative decoding." The right durable rule is "do not store separate assistant models as a hard requirement of speculative decoding." That is the level of update supported by the public sources, and it is the level that future runs should preserve.\n\nThere is also a memory-management reason to keep this page long. Without the extra explanation, readers often overcorrect in the opposite direction and decide that assistant models are now obsolete or that the self-speculative path is the new canonical form of the method. The public paper does not justify that leap. It broadens the design space; it does not collapse it to one winning recipe. For a reusable reference database, that distinction is crucial. The validated update is about admissible architectures, not about a permanent ranking of architectures.\n\nAnother durable takeaway from the public paper is that later variants should be stored as structured corrections to old beliefs, not as replacements for the entire old belief bundle. The old bundle contains at least two different claims: there is usually a draft path and there is usually a separate draft model. The first claim survives. The second becomes conditional. A careful database separates those claims so later maintenance is possible. This page is designed to support exactly that kind of structured maintenance.',
  'speculative decoding | self speculative | draft model | verify'
);

INSERT INTO documents (id, slug, title, kind, status, reliability, updated_at, owner, summary, body, tags) VALUES (
  'browser:spec_speed_003',
  'speculative-decoding-speedup-rule',
  'Speedup Rule for Deployment',
  'benchmark_note',
  'validated',
  'high',
  '2026-02-18',
  'serving-benchmarks',
  'Public framework documentation and benchmark notes agree that practical speedup depends on draft cost, acceptance, and serving-system fit together; acceptance alone is not enough.',
  'Reference URLs: https://docs.vllm.ai/en/latest/features/speculative_decoding/ ; https://huggingface.co/blog/dynamic_speculation_lookahead ; https://huggingface.co/blog/assisted-generation.\n\nThis note is grounded in public serving and benchmarking material rather than the original theory paper. The reason it matters is that many people learn speculative decoding from a paper or a talk and then immediately ask a deployment question: if the acceptance rate is high, are we guaranteed to be faster? The combined answer from modern framework documentation is no. Acceptance helps, but it competes with the cost of drafting, the cost of verification, the batching regime, and the details of the serving stack. The vLLM documentation repeatedly frames speculative decoding as a serving feature whose utility depends on the workload shape, and the Hugging Face dynamic speculation writeup includes concrete benchmark rows where heuristic choices do not help and can even slow the system down.\n\nThe durable rule for the database is therefore multi-factor. A deployment win requires the draft path to be cheap enough, the accepted fraction to be high enough, and the system regime to make that trade beneficial. Public benchmark tables in the Hugging Face note are especially useful here because they show that a heuristic policy can deliver no significant speedup or even a slowdown for some model pairs. That observation blocks a common but misleading shortcut: acceptance is a useful signal, but it does not dominate all the other costs.\n\nThe fallback explanation for disappointing results follows directly from the same sources. If verification remains expensive or if acceptance stays low, the latency gain can disappear even though the method is still exact. In other words, correctness and speedup are separate axes. The note preserves that split on purpose so that future runs do not collapse a semantic guarantee into an engineering promise.\n\nIt is also worth recording why newer public sources talk so much about dynamic or adaptive speculation. A fixed heuristic for how many tokens to draft can look attractive in one benchmark regime and then underperform in another. The Hugging Face dynamic speculation article is valuable because it does not merely offer a new heuristic; it demonstrates that policy choice is itself part of the deployment problem. That pushes the durable rule one level higher. The rule is not that one public heuristic always wins. The rule is that speculation policy interacts with the model pair, workload, and serving stack, so a system that never revisits its policy can easily leave performance on the table or even regress.\n\nPublic serving docs also encourage a more grounded question about where the method is likely to matter. The useful framing is not "speculative decoding is good." The useful framing is "in what serving regimes does cheap drafting plus verification actually improve latency." The most stable public answer points toward latency-sensitive settings, memory-sensitive inference paths, and deployments where verification can be amortized effectively relative to what is accepted. This should not be turned into a theorem, but it is a much better durable heuristic than the simplistic acceptance-only story.\n\nAnother benefit of storing the multi-factor rule is that it remains useful even as frameworks evolve. vLLM, Hugging Face, and other public implementations may differ in feature support, policy defaults, and supported draft mechanisms. Those details will change. The underlying durable memory should survive the framework churn. It should continue to say that speedup depends on draft cost, acceptance, and system fit together, and that verification overhead or low acceptance can erase the gain even while the method remains exact.\n\nThat last sentence is especially important because it keeps the knowledge base from producing the wrong kind of postmortem. If a deployment benchmark disappoints, the correct conclusion is not automatically that speculative decoding failed as a concept. The correct conclusion may simply be that the chosen pair, policy, or serving regime did not make the trade favorable. This note therefore stores both the optimistic and pessimistic sides of the public record: the method can deliver real gains, but only under cost conditions that survive end-to-end measurement.\n\nThe practical memory rule that follows is simple but easy to forget. When asked why a deployment did or did not speed up, do not answer with one scalar. Answer with a small cost model: draft path cost, acceptance, verification overhead, and serving-system fit. That rule is more portable across frameworks than any one benchmark table, and it is exactly the kind of portable operational knowledge a durable database should preserve.\n\nIt is also the right antidote to benchmark overconfidence. A single positive benchmark row can tempt a team to treat a pair or policy as universally good. The public framework material argues for a more disciplined view. Measure the end-to-end trade under the serving conditions that matter, and keep exactness separate from the latency result. That is the deployment rule worth storing.\n\nOne final operational reminder belongs here. Serving teams often ask for a single number that predicts whether speculation will help. The public record does not provide one, and this note should not pretend otherwise. What it provides is a repeatable evaluation frame. Check the draft cost, check the acceptance, check the verification overhead, and check the workload regime. If those conditions align, the method can be valuable. If they do not, the method may stay exact while the business win disappears. That is the durable deployment lesson.',
  'speculative decoding | speedup | acceptance | system fit | overhead'
);

INSERT INTO documents (id, slug, title, kind, status, reliability, updated_at, owner, summary, body, tags) VALUES (
  'browser:uad_004',
  'universal-assisted-decoding-note',
  'Universal Assisted Decoding and Tokenizer Alignment',
  'framework_note',
  'validated',
  'high',
  '2026-02-21',
  'framework-research',
  'Recent Hugging Face documentation makes a narrower tokenizer claim than older assisted-decoding guides: same-tokenizer pairing is common, but cross-tokenizer assistance is possible when alignment machinery is provided.',
  'Reference URLs: https://huggingface.co/docs/transformers/v4.46.0/en/generation_strategies ; https://huggingface.co/blog/dynamic_speculation_lookahead.\n\nThis note exists because tokenizer assumptions are easy to harden into false rules. Earlier assisted-decoding documentation often presented the simplest case: a main model and a smaller assistant model sharing the same tokenizer. That framing is practical and still appears in public docs because it keeps the implementation story simple. However, the same documentation now also describes Universal Assisted Decoding, which allows the main and assistant models to use different tokenizers as long as alignment and re-encoding are handled explicitly. The right durable conclusion is not that tokenizers never matter; it is that same-tokenizer pairing is a convenient baseline, not an immutable law.\n\nThe distinction matters for long-lived memory. If a user only remembers the older simplified setup, they may treat same-tokenizer pairing as a theoretical requirement of speculative decoding itself. That is too strong. The public docs make it clear that tokenizer compatibility can be engineered in more than one way, and newer library features were added precisely because the earlier assumption was too narrow for many real model pairs. This is similar to the draft-model update: an older practical default was real, but the design space later widened.\n\nFor the database, the clean answer is that cross-tokenizer assistance is possible with explicit alignment support. That formulation stays faithful to the docs while avoiding a second overcorrection. The note does not claim that tokenizer mismatch is free or universally preferable. It only records that newer public tooling removed the need to treat same-tokenizer pairing as a hard requirement.\n\nThe public documentation is useful here because it encodes both the old default and the newer relaxation in one place. Same-tokenizer pairing remains the easiest path to explain, and it remains operationally convenient. That is why it still appears in examples. But the presence of Universal Assisted Decoding in current docs means the strongest old version of the rule is no longer safe as durable memory. A strong note should therefore preserve the default as historical context while storing the updated design space as the lasting rule.\n\nThis distinction mirrors the draft-model update from self-speculative decoding. In both cases, an early implementation assumption was real and useful. In both cases, later public material widened the design space. The knowledge base should not erase the old assumption as if it had never been true in practice. Instead, it should reclassify it: same tokenizer is a common and simple regime, not a theorem about what speculative decoding fundamentally requires.\n\nA second reason to store this carefully is that tokenizer mismatch introduces real engineering considerations. Alignment and re-encoding are not free. The public docs do not say that cross-tokenizer assistance is universally better than same-tokenizer assistance. They say it is possible when the framework provides explicit support. That is a narrower and more durable claim. It keeps the note faithful to the docs while still correcting the older false rule.\n\nFor future runs, the ideal one sentence memory is therefore: tokenizer alignment matters operationally, but cross-tokenizer assisted decoding is possible when alignment machinery is provided. That sentence preserves what is practically important without turning the simpler historical setup into an artificial law.\n\nThis page is deliberately explicit because tokenizer assumptions become sticky very quickly in infrastructure teams. Once a rule sounds implementation specific, people stop checking whether it was a framework limitation, an example simplification, or an algorithmic requirement. Universal Assisted Decoding exists in current public documentation precisely because the original simplification was too narrow for the real model landscape. A durable portal should therefore preserve both halves of the truth: same-tokenizer pairing remains the easiest and most common path, yet the broader supported design space is now public and should update long-lived memory.\n\nOne more operational caution belongs here. Cross-tokenizer assistance is possible with alignment support, but it is not free and it is not a reason to ignore all compatibility questions. Alignment logic, re-encoding, and framework support still matter. This is why the validated conclusion is framed as possible with alignment, not trivial or universally preferable. The point of the update is to weaken an absolute rule, not to replace it with a new absolute rule.\n\nThat is also why this page belongs in validated evidence instead of the low-confidence bucket. It does not turn a broad trend into a slogan. It preserves the public update at the level the docs actually support: same-tokenizer assistance is a common baseline, while cross-tokenizer assistance is possible when the framework provides explicit alignment support.\n\nA final durable rule can therefore be written in two layers. The implementation layer says same-tokenizer assistance is still simpler and still common. The capability layer says cross-tokenizer assistance is possible when the framework supplies explicit alignment support. Storing both layers prevents the database from drifting into either of the two symmetric mistakes: treating the older baseline as a theorem, or treating the newer flexibility as if it removed all engineering cost.',
  'speculative decoding | universal assisted decoding | tokenizer | alignment'
);

INSERT INTO documents (id, slug, title, kind, status, reliability, updated_at, owner, summary, body, tags) VALUES (
  'browser:spec_noise_001',
  'acceptance-alone-shortcut',
  'Acceptance-First Tuning Shortcut',
  'legacy_note',
  'superseded',
  'low',
  '2025-10-01',
  'legacy-serving',
  'This lower-confidence note over-focuses on acceptance as the main tuning signal. It is derived from real public heuristic material, but it is too narrow to use as the final deployment rule.',
  'Reference URLs: https://huggingface.co/blog/dynamic_speculation_lookahead ; https://huggingface.co/blog/assisted-generation.\n\nThis note captures a real pattern that appeared in public assisted-generation material: operators and library code often tuned the number of drafted tokens by looking at whether previous proposals were accepted. That heuristic is not invented. It is public, practical, and useful as a control signal. The problem is what happens when that local control signal becomes a global belief. Teams start to speak as if high acceptance is sufficient evidence that the serving path will be faster, and they stop auditing draft cost, verification overhead, batching behavior, or the hardware regime.\n\nThat overreach is why this page is marked low reliability for durable memory even though it is grounded in real public material. The Hugging Face dynamic speculation article itself is careful: it compares heuristic and dynamic policies and shows benchmark rows where the heuristic path can underperform. The public evidence therefore supports a weaker statement than this shortcut note tries to preserve. Acceptance is useful, but acceptance by itself does not settle the latency question.\n\nA model that inspects this page should learn something from it, but it should not keep the headline as a final answer. The durable database should remember the higher-level deployment rule from the validated note, not the narrower operator shortcut from this legacy writeup.\n\nThe reason this page remains valuable as a low-confidence source is that it records how a misconception is formed. The misconception does not come from nowhere. It comes from taking a real local control signal and promoting it into a full deployment theory. That is exactly the kind of error that can survive in an organization for months if nobody preserves the distinction between useful heuristics and durable truths.\n\nThere is another reason to reject this page as final memory. It collapses several distinct costs into one number. Acceptance rate says something about how often drafted tokens are usable. It does not directly say whether the draft model was cheap enough, whether verification was amortized well enough, whether the batch regime was friendly, or whether the hardware path made speculation worthwhile. The dynamic speculation post exists precisely because those conditions vary and because a static heuristic can miss them.\n\nSo the correct handling of this page is not deletion but downgrading. A good agent should preserve the weaker lesson: acceptance is one meaningful signal for speculation control. It should reject the stronger lesson: high acceptance by itself guarantees or nearly guarantees an end-to-end speedup. That stronger lesson is the reason this page is stored as low reliability evidence instead of validated evidence.\n\nAnother reason this page is useful as a distractor is that it feels operationally sophisticated. It talks about tuning, signals, and control loops, which makes it sound more nuanced than a simple hype sentence. But that sophistication is local, not global. The note is still wrong as durable truth because it elevates one operational signal above the complete cost picture documented in better public sources. A strong model should therefore extract the limited truth and reject the inflated conclusion.\n\nThis page also captures a broader pattern that appears in systems work. Once a useful heuristic is easy to measure, teams start treating it as if it were the objective itself. The public dynamic speculation material is valuable precisely because it pushes back on that tendency with benchmark evidence. Some policies that look natural on paper do not help uniformly in practice. That public evidence is why this page must stay in the portal as a learnable but rejectable artifact.\n\nIf this note is ever copied into durable memory without qualification, the database will start making a predictable mistake. It will explain deployment outcomes as if the acceptance story were sufficient, and it will underweight the costs that actually decide the end-to-end result. That is why the right final use of this page is negative evidence: inspect it, understand why it sounds plausible, and then keep only the narrower lesson that acceptance is informative but incomplete.\n\nOne more reason to keep this page in the portal is pedagogical. It forces the agent to distinguish between a true local heuristic and a false global conclusion. That distinction is the core skill this task is trying to measure. The heuristic is real. The universal rule is not.\n\nThis page also demonstrates why low-confidence evidence is not the same thing as fabricated evidence. Everything here can be traced back to real public discussions of speculation control. The failure is in scope, not in existence. The page takes a local tuning idea and expands it into a universal deployment claim. A strong model should notice that inflation and reject it while still understanding where the shorter rule of thumb came from.\n\nA final warning is worth storing here. Operational shortcuts spread faster than measured cost models because they are easier to repeat in meetings and benchmark reports. That social reality is one reason the acceptance-only story persists. A durable knowledge base should therefore treat this page as a documented temptation rather than a reliable rule.',
  'speculative decoding | acceptance | heuristic | shortcut'
);

INSERT INTO documents (id, slug, title, kind, status, reliability, updated_at, owner, summary, body, tags) VALUES (
  'browser:spec_noise_002',
  'same-tokenizer-assumption-note',
  'Same-Tokenizer Assistant Assumption',
  'legacy_note',
  'superseded',
  'low',
  '2025-11-10',
  'legacy-serving',
  'This lower-confidence note preserves an older implementation default from public assisted-decoding docs: same-tokenizer pairing. It is real, but it is now too narrow to keep as a durable rule.',
  'Reference URLs: https://huggingface.co/docs/transformers/v4.46.0/en/generation_strategies ; https://huggingface.co/blog/assisted-generation.\n\nThis page is based on a real public implementation assumption. In older assisted-decoding explanations, the target model and assistant model were usually introduced as compatible checkpoints that shared the same tokenizer. That was an understandable default because it removed a complicated alignment problem from the first generation of examples and documentation. For that reason, many operator notes repeated the same-tokenizer rule as if it were part of the underlying algorithm rather than part of the example setup.\n\nThe reason this page is marked superseded is not that the original implementation advice was fake. It is that later public documentation expanded the design space and explained Universal Assisted Decoding. Once that update exists, the stronger rule in this page becomes too rigid for a durable knowledge base. A same-tokenizer pairing is still a common and convenient regime, but it is no longer the only public path that should be remembered.\n\nA good agent should therefore reject this note as a final rule while still understanding why it existed. The correct durable memory is that tokenizer alignment matters operationally, yet cross-tokenizer assistance is possible when the framework provides the required alignment and mapping machinery.\n\nThis is a useful low-confidence page because it represents a very common historical note shape: a practical default gets copied so many times that it starts to look like a theorem. The public assisted-generation article made the simple setup easy to remember, so the same-tokenizer rule spread widely. That history is real. What changed later is that framework documentation exposed a broader implementation space. The page becomes low confidence not because it was always false, but because it became too strong once newer public evidence existed.\n\nThe durable correction is therefore subtle. A same-tokenizer assistant remains convenient. It is still a good default example. It is still common in practice. What is no longer safe is the stronger sentence that speculative decoding requires same-tokenizer pairing. The later docs weaken that sentence by introducing explicit alignment support. A careful knowledge base should preserve that weakening rather than replacing one overstatement with another.\n\nThis page is particularly valuable as a distractor because the wrong claim and the right claim share so much surface vocabulary. Both talk about tokenizers, assistants, and compatibility. A weak reader may think the newer documentation only adds implementation details, when in fact it changes the logical status of the old rule. The old rule says same-tokenizer pairing is required. The newer public record says same-tokenizer pairing is a common baseline and that cross-tokenizer assistance is possible with explicit support. That shift from required to baseline is exactly the kind of shift durable memory systems often fail to preserve.\n\nThere is also a process lesson embedded here. When framework features expand, old notes do not become useless immediately. They become conditionally correct. A strong knowledge base needs to track that change in status instead of treating notes as simply true or false. This page remains historically informative because it explains why many engineers learned the same-tokenizer story first. It becomes low confidence because it is no longer safe as a final answer.\n\nIf a model reads only this page, it can still build a superficially coherent answer. That is why the page is an effective distractor. The answer would sound practical, conservative, and implementation aware. It would also be incomplete in a way that matters for later design decisions. The correct durable response is to downgrade the page, retain the historical explanation, and replace the final rule with the broader statement supported by later public documentation.\n\nThe page is therefore not fake evidence. It is outdated evidence. That is exactly why it is useful in a hard task. The model has to recognize the difference between an outdated operational default and a durable final rule.\n\nA last reason to keep this page long is that the historical mistake can otherwise look trivial. In practice it is not trivial. Many teams learned speculative decoding through the easiest assistant-model examples, and those examples made same-tokenizer pairing feel natural and universal. The newer public documentation does not say those examples were wrong. It says they were narrower than the now documented design space. The right durable response is therefore reinterpretation, not deletion. That reinterpretation step is what this distractor is designed to force.\n\nThere is a final methodological point as well. When a practical default survives long enough, it becomes hard to remember that it started as a convenience. This page is meant to surface that memory failure explicitly. The original convenience was real. The final durable rule is broader. A strong model should preserve both facts without confusing one for the other.\n\nThat final durable rule is simple to state but easy to forget: same-tokenizer assistance is a common historical baseline, not a law of speculative decoding. Once newer public tooling documents alignment support, long-lived memory must be updated accordingly.',
  'speculative decoding | tokenizer | assistant model | legacy assumption'
);

COMMIT;
